.TH "SL" "1" "2026" "sl v2026.1" "Steam Locomotive"
.SH NAME
sl \- Steam Locomotive runs across your terminal
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]sl\f[R] [\f[B]\-d\f[R]] [\f[I]version\f[R]|\f[I]subcommand\f[R]]
[\f[I]options\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]sl\f[R] is a wrapper script that dispatches to versioned Steam
Locomotive binaries.
When you mistype \f[B]ls\f[R], a steam locomotive runs across your
terminal as a gentle punishment.
.PP
Four versions are available: \f[B]1985\f[R] (the original),
\f[B]2010\f[R], \f[B]2023\f[R], and \f[B]2026\f[R].
Without a version argument, the latest available version is selected
automatically.
.PP
The \f[B]2026\f[R] version detects existing text on the terminal screen
and begins sweeping (pushing text off via the \f[B]dch2\f[R] terminal
capability) only when the train reaches it, preserving text that the
train has not yet passed.
The train enters gradually from beyond the right edge of the screen,
like the original 1985 version.
.SH REQUIREMENTS
The 2026 version captures the terminal screen content to detect existing
text.
This feature currently supports the following terminal emulators on
macOS:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]iTerm2\f[R] (iTerm.app)
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Apple Terminal\f[R] (Terminal.app)
.PP
On unsupported terminals or platforms, the train always sweeps
(equivalent to the 2023 behavior).
Other versions (1985, 2010, 2023) work on any terminal.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-d\f[R]
Show debug information on the last line before running.
.TP
\f[B]\-a\f[R] (2026 only)
Sweep the entire screen.
Without this option, only the 7\-line area where the train runs is
swept.
With \f[B]\-a\f[R], all screen lines are swept and the sweep start
position is determined from the full screen content rather than just the
train area.
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R] (2026 only)
Dry run.
Show debug information and exit without running the train.
.SH VERSIONS
.TP
\f[B]1985\f[R]
The original SL, written in K&R C with curses.
Output is filtered through a per\-character delay for a retro feel.
.TP
\f[B]2010\f[R]
Updated version using direct terminal control instead of curses.
.TP
\f[B]2023\f[R]
Unicode art version with box\-drawing characters.
Always sweeps text from the left edge.
.TP
\f[B]2026\f[R]
Screen\-aware version.
Detects text on the terminal and sweeps only when the train reaches it.
Enters from beyond the right edge of the screen to preserve right\-side
text.
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
These subcommands are primarily for debugging the screen capture and
sweep detection mechanism.
.TP
\f[B]capture\f[R]
Dump the captured visible screen text to stdout.
.TP
\f[B]sweep\-area\f[R]
Show the 7\-line area where the train runs.
.TP
\f[B]clear\-col\f[R]
Print the column number where sweeping should start.
.TP
\f[B]debug\f[R]
Show detailed sweep area analysis with visual output.
.TP
\f[B]mark\f[R]
Draw a visual marker at the sweep start column and print the column
number.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]SL_SWEEP_COL\f[R]
Passed internally to the sl\-2026 binary.
Specifies the column at which sweeping begins.
.TP
\f[B]SL_SWEEP_ALL\f[R]
Passed internally to the sl\-2026 binary.
When set, sweeps all screen lines instead of just the train area.
.SH INSTALL
.IP
